caption: Table 1: Imputation accuracy in MAE. MAE scores are enlarged by 10 times.
description: This table presents the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) scores achieved by different imputation methods on eight benchmark datasets.  The MAE is a common metric used to evaluate the accuracy of missing value imputation, representing the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual values. Lower MAE indicates better imputation performance. The table compares M³-Impute with several baseline and state-of-the-art imputation methods, including statistical methods (Mean, SVD, Spectral), iterative imputation methods (Mice, KNN), and deep learning-based methods (GAIN, MIWAE, GRAPE, Miracle, HyperImpute).  The MAE values are multiplied by 10 for better readability.

description: This table presents the results of an ablation study on the M³-Impute model, investigating the impact of varying the number of peer samples (size of P) used in the Sample Correlation Unit (SCU) and different values of epsilon (ϵ) used in the model initialization.  It shows how the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) changes with different values of |P| and ϵ across various datasets. The goal is to find the optimal values that minimize the MAE, which can provide insight into how to tune these hyperparameters for better performance in different applications.
